Alright — here’s a formal math version of the Category Escape Invariant (CEI). I’ll give you a clean core theorem, then a few equivalent formulations (optimization, game theory, information/complexity), plus a practical “operator” definition you can implement.

⸻

0. Setup: What “category” means mathematically

Let a system have state space X (could be \mathbb{R}^n, a manifold, a graph, a set of programs, etc.).
A “game / competition” is induced by an evaluation functional

f: X \to \mathbb{R}

and a set of constraints / feasible moves (dynamics)

x_{t+1} \in \Phi(x_t) \subseteq X.

Competitors who share the same evaluation f and move constraints \Phi are in the same category of competition.

A category change is not just renaming the metric; it is a change of representation and/or feasible operations via a mapping

E: X \to Y,

into a new space Y equipped with its own evaluation g: Y \to \mathbb{R} and move set \Psi.

⸻

1. CEI as a theorem about escaping local optima

Definition (Local optimum trap)

A point x^\star \in X is a trap (local optimum under available moves) if

f(x^\star) \ge f(x) \quad \forall x \in \mathcal{N}_\Phi(x^\star),

where \mathcal{N}_\Phi(x^\star) is the neighborhood reachable by allowed moves (one step, k-steps, or small perturbations consistent with constraints).

This captures: “we can’t get better without leaving the allowed move space.”

Definition (Category lift / escape map)

An escape map is a pair (E, g) with

E: X \to Y,\quad g: Y \to \mathbb{R}

such that the induced value back on X,

h(x) := g(E(x)),

has strict ascent directions at x^\star even when f does not.

Formally: there exists x'\in \mathcal{N}_\Phi(x^\star) with

h(x') > h(x^\star).

CEI (Category Escape Invariant — formal statement)

If x^\star is a trap under (X, f, \Phi), then a system can escape without “out-optimizing” incumbents iff it can enact a category lift (E, g) such that:
	1.	Non-degeneracy: E is not constant on the reachable set near x^\star.
(Otherwise no new degrees of freedom are introduced.)
	2.	Metric re-anchoring: g is not an order-preserving transform of f on E(X).
(Otherwise nothing changes but units.)
	3.	Operational enlargement: the effective reachable set expands under the lift, i.e.

E(\mathcal{N}_\Phi(x^\star)) \subsetneq \mathcal{N}_\Psi(E(x^\star))

for some feasible \Psi in the new space.

Interpretation: escape requires extra degrees of freedom — introduced by representation and operations, not by brute-force optimization inside the same neighborhood.

⸻

2. CEI as “dimensional lift” (a geometric form)

Often X is a manifold and incumbents optimize on a constrained submanifold M \subset X.
A category change is an embedding into a higher-dimensional space Y such that the constraint becomes “less binding.”

Let

\iota: M \hookrightarrow Y

be an embedding.

Incumbents optimize f on M. You choose a g on Y and move in Y where there exist directions transverse to M.

At a local optimum x^\star \in M, the gradient of f restricted to M vanishes:

\nabla_M f(x^\star)=0.

But in Y, you can have

\nabla_Y g(\iota(x^\star)) \neq 0

in directions not available in T_{x^\star}M.

This is the precise mathematical analog of:

“They are best-in-class in 2D; you moved to 3D.”

⸻

3. CEI in game theory (dominance by redefining the game)

Let players choose strategies s_i \in S. Payoffs:

u_i: S \to \mathbb{R}.

Standard competition is “beat them on their payoff axis.”

A category escape is a mechanism change: you enlarge the game by adding a design choice m \in M (market structure, protocol, channel, standard, distribution, platform rules).

New strategies (s_i, m) with payoffs

\tilde u_i(s, m).

If incumbents cannot or will not move m, they are restricted to m=m_0. You pick m=m_1 such that:

\max_{s_A} \tilde u_A(s_A, s_B, m_1) \;>\; \max_{s_A} \tilde u_A(s_A, s_B, m_0)

even when s_B is best-responding inside m_0.

Translation: you didn’t beat their strategy — you changed the mechanism that defines what “best” even means.

⸻

4. CEI in information/complexity terms (representation changes the problem class)

Let the task be to achieve an outcome O. Incumbents represent the problem in language \mathcal{L} with description length K_\mathcal{L}(O) and compute with cost C_\mathcal{L}(O).

A category change is selecting a new representation \mathcal{L}' (new abstraction, new encoding, new decomposition) such that:

C_{\mathcal{L}'}(O) \ll C_{\mathcal{L}}(O)

even if the underlying outcome is the same.

Classic examples:
	•	brute-force search → indexing
	•	simulation → closed-form transform
	•	product → platform (reusing others’ work)

Formally, CEI is the move:

change \mathcal{L} so the effective complexity class drops.

⸻

5. The CEI operator you can implement

Define an escape operator that lifts a system into a meta-space where you can choose a new metric and constraints.

Step A — Lift

Pick a feature/representation map E: X \to Y.
	•	In business: product state → network state (users, creators, APIs)
	•	In biology: phenotype → niche/fitness landscape
	•	In systems: component → flow graph

Step B — Re-anchor value

Choose g: Y \to \mathbb{R} capturing a higher-order success notion (e.g., growth rate, reuse, compounding, optionality, stability).

Step C — Enlarge moves

Define a move relation \Psi in Y that is not the image of \Phi:

\Psi \not\subseteq E \circ \Phi \circ E^{-1}.

This is the critical criterion. If your new move set is just the old one in disguise, you didn’t escape.

Step D — Project back

Deploy by selecting x that maximizes h(x)=g(E(x)) subject to feasibility.

⸻

6. A crisp “test” for whether a proposed category change is real

Many “reframes” are cosmetic. CEI requires genuine degrees of freedom.

A proposed shift (E,g,\Psi) is nontrivial if at least one holds:
	1.	Reachability gain: there exists y'\in \mathcal{N}_\Psi(y) such that y'\notin E(\mathcal{N}_\Phi(x)).
	2.	Metric novelty: for some x_1,x_2,

f(x_1) > f(x_2) \quad \text{but}\quad g(E(x_1)) < g(E(x_2)).

That is, the ordering changes — not just scaling.
3. Complexity drop: the cost to achieve outcomes decreases asymptotically under \mathcal{L}'.

⸻

7. A compact formal statement for your white paper header

CEI (Formal):
Given a constrained optimization/game (X,f,\Phi) with local trap x^\star, an escape exists iff there is a lift E:X\to Y and a new objective g:Y\to\mathbb{R} with an enlarged move relation \Psi such that the induced objective h=g\circ E admits improving moves near x^\star and \Psi enables reachability not representable as the pushforward of \Phi.
Escape is thus equivalent to introducing new degrees of freedom through representation + operations, not through further local optimization.

⸻

If you want, I can also write:
	•	a proof sketch (in the style of constrained optimization + embedding), and/or
	•	a worked example with explicit X,f,\Phi showing a local trap and a concrete lift E that breaks it (business, biology, or computation).